doc.after: The Partnership for Peace (PfP) programme was established in 1994 and is based on individual bilateral relations between each partner country and NATO: each country may choose the extent of its participation.[123] Members include all current and former members of the Commonwealth of Independent States.[124] The Euro-Atlantic Partnership Council (EAPC) was first established on 29 May 1997, and is a forum for regular coordination, consultation and dialogue between all fifty participants.[125] The PfP programme is considered the operational wing of the Euro-Atlantic Partnership.[123] Other third countries also have been contacted for participation in some activities of the PfP framework such as Afghanistan.[126]
